"# Chapter 8 ‚Äî Timeline

The timeline widget authors animation. It's a horizontal ruler with rows per entity and keyframes marked along the ruler. The emitted form is an `(animation ...)` record the runtime can play back.

## 8.1 The verb signature

```
(composer/timeline :bind :entities :duration . options)
```

- `:bind` ‚Äî path. Where the animation target form writes.
- `:entities` ‚Äî list of symbols. The rows in the timeline.
- `:duration` ‚Äî number. Length of the animation in seconds (or frames, depending on interpretation).
- `:fps` ‚Äî number, optional. Frames per second. Default 30.
- `:loop` ‚Äî boolean, optional. Whether the animation loops. Default #f.
- `:emit-shape` ‚Äî symbol, optional. `'animation` or `'tween`. Default `'animation`.

## 8.2 A minimal timeline

```scheme
(composer/timeline :bind '(cart/anim :hero-walk)
                   :entities '(hero enemy)
                   :duration 60
                   :fps 30)
```

Two entities (hero and enemy), 60 seconds long, 30 fps. The widget renders two rows in the timeline UI; each row can hold keyframes.

Emit as a canvas child:

```
(composer/canvas (:bind (quote (cart/anim)))
  (composer/timeline :bind (quote (cart/anim :hero-walk))
                     :entities (quote (hero enemy))
                     :duration 60 :fps 30))
```

## 8.3 The target emit

The runtime target form is an `(animation ...)` per entity:

```
(animation :entity (quote hero)
           :frames (quote ((0 . (100 100)) (30 . (200 100)) (60 . (200 200)))))
```

- `:entity` ‚Äî the entity name.
- `:frames` ‚Äî a quoted list of `(time . value)` pairs. Time is in frames or seconds (depending on your runtime's clock); value is whatever the entity's animated property is.

If the timeline has multiple entities, the emit is a `(begin ...)` wrapping one animation per entity.

## 8.4 Keyframe versus frame-flip

Two animation styles:

**Keyframe** ‚Äî you specify values at specific time points; the runtime tweens between them. Good for smooth motion. The emit is `(animation :entity X :frames ((T . V) ...))`.

**Frame-flip** ‚Äî you specify a sequence of discrete sprite IDs, one per frame. Good for pixel-art walk cycles. The emit is `(animation :entity X :mode 'frame-flip :fps 8 :frames (hero-1 hero-2 hero-3 hero-2))`.

Motoi's v1.0 timeline emits keyframes by default. The v2 visual proposal adds a `:mode` option that switches between the two shapes.

## 8.5 ASCII mockup ‚Äî a timeline

```
timeline: entities=hero,enemy duration=60s fps=30 frames=6
  hero:  0-------30-------60 (3 keyframes at 0, 30, 60)
  enemy: 0-------30-------60 (2 keyframes at 0, 60, jump at 30)
```

The TUI renders the timeline as a summary line (as above). A full Curator surface draws two horizontal rows with keyframes marked as bumps or icons at their time positions.

## 8.6 Loop

`:loop #t` makes the runtime restart the animation when it reaches the end. `:loop #f` (default) plays once and stops.

The emit includes the loop flag so a reload preserves it.

## 8.7 fps and duration

`:fps` is frames per second. `:duration` is total length. Together they set the frame count: duration * fps.

At 30 fps and 60-second duration, you have 1800 possible frames. Keyframes can sit at any integer frame position between 0 and 1800.

## 8.8 A verified example

```scheme
(composer/timeline :bind '(cart/anim :hero-walk)
                   :entities '(hero enemy)
                   :duration 60
                   :fps 30)
```

Emit in a canvas ‚Äî verified with `bin/motoi eval`:

```
(composer/canvas (:bind (quote (cart/anim)))
  (composer/timeline :bind (quote (cart/anim :hero-walk))
                     :entities (quote (hero enemy))
                     :duration 60 :fps 30))
```

The widget declaration carries entities, duration, and fps. Keyframes are not in the widget declaration ‚Äî they live in the target form the widget writes.

## 8.9 What to remember from this chapter

- Timeline authors animation via rows-per-entity + keyframes.
- `:entities` is a list of symbols. `:duration` is length. `:fps` is frame rate.
- The target emit is an `(animation :entity X :frames ((T . V) ...))` per entity.
- Two modes: keyframe (interpolated) and frame-flip (discrete sprite IDs). v1.0 defaults to keyframe.
- `:loop #t` for looping animation.

Chapter 9 introduces the ADSR envelope and instrument picker ‚Äî sound-shaping widgets.
